{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JoYUt8kny7hrPnKJfo8fTe","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n3\tdate: 2026-05-27\n4\ttarget_release: 0.7.0\n5\tdesc: Pack 1 schema-migration + ingest double-write decisions for\n6\t  the binary-quantization data-encoding change locked by\n7\t  ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md.\n8\tblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (schema +\n9\t  writer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs\n10\t  (existing fixture continuity); dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md\n11\t  (implements its Pack 1 section).\n12\tstatus: draft fix-1 (consumed by Pack 1 implementation)\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\t# 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n16\t\n17\tThis memo resolves the open design questions called out in\n18\t`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md` § \"Pack 1\"\n19\tand § \"Open items the implementing agent should escalate to HITL\"\n20\tso that Pack 1 implementation can land mechanically. Pairs with\n21\tADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md (which records the *what*); this\n22\tmemo records the *exact shape*.\n23\t\n24\tScope: Pack 1 only — schema migration + writer double-write. No\n25\treader changes. The Pack 2 query rewrite is out of scope for this\n26\tmemo and is owned by a separate design pass when Pack 2 starts.\n27\t\n28\t## D1 — Sibling column vs. sibling table\n29\t\n30\t**Decision: sibling column on `vector_default`.**\n31\t\n32\tThe migrated declaration is:\n33\t\n34\t```\n35\tCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n36\t  embedding float[<dim>],\n37\t  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n38\t  source_type TEXT partition key,\n39\t  kind TEXT,\n40\t  created_at INTEGER\n41\t);\n42\t```\n43\t\n44\t(`<dim>` = 768 for the current default profile; the existing\n45\t`ensure_vector_partition` builds the dimension from\n46\t`load_default_profile` at `lib.rs:3278-3283`.)\n47\t\n48\t- Alternatives weighed: sibling table `vector_default_bin` (one\n49\t  extra join on every read; fan-out cost on the Pack 2 reader; two\n50\t  inserts per row instead of one; two DELETE sites in every\n51\t  excise / rebuild path — `lib.rs:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`).\n52\t- Citation: the sqlite-vec binary-quant guide demonstrates the\n53\t  exact mixed-flavour declaration\n54\t  `create virtual table vec_movies using vec0(synopsis_embedding\n55\t  float[768], synopsis_embedding_coarse bit[768])`\n56\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html);\n57\t  confirmed empirically by WebFetch on 2026-05-27 against the\n58\t  same page.\n59\t\n60\tThe sibling-column shape is the default in the handoff\n61\t(§ 1.1) and in the ADR (§ 2 / Pack 1.1). The sibling-table\n62\tfallback remains documented in both as a recovery path **only if**\n63\tthe 16-metadata-column cap is exceeded (see D2) — that is not the\n64\tcase for Pack 1.\n65\t\n66\t## D2 — Metadata column inventory (vec0 16-col cap)\n67\t\n68\tvec0 caps metadata columns at 16 and partition keys at 4\n69\t(`dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md:70-71`). The Pack 1\n70\tschema lands the minimum-viable set with headroom for the\n71\treal-workload extension already foreseen by the ADR and the\n72\tHITL doc.\n73\t\n74\tPack 1 column inventory on `vector_default`:\n75\t\n76\t| # | Column            | Type           | Role                  | Source                                                         |\n77\t|---|-------------------|----------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n78\t| 0 | `rowid`           | INTEGER        | (implicit pk)         | `cursor` (existing — `lib.rs:2845-2851`).                      |\n79\t| 1 | `embedding`       | `float[<dim>]` | vector                | existing — `vec_quantize_binary` input + Pack 2 rerank.        |\n80\t| 2 | `embedding_bin`   | `bit[<dim>]`   | quantized vector      | `vec_quantize_binary(embedding)` at write time.                |\n81\t| 3 | `source_type`     | `TEXT`         | **partition key**     | derived from `kind` per D3.                                    |\n82\t| 4 | `kind`            | `TEXT`         | metadata col          | existing `ProjectionOutcome::Success.kind` (`lib.rs:2841`).    |\n83\t| 5 | `created_at`      | `INTEGER`     | metadata col          | UNIX seconds at write time (mirrors `excised_at` pattern at `lib.rs:2206`). |\n84\t\n85\tHeadroom: **11 free metadata column slots + 3 free partition-key\n86\tslots** after Pack 1.\n87\t\n88\tDeferred to Pack 2 / 0.7.1 (NOT landed in Pack 1):\n89\t\n90\t- `tags`, `project_mentions` — named in the handoff § 1.1 but not\n91\t  populated by today's writer; the chunk record carries no such\n92\t  field. Wiring requires upstream code changes that are out of\n93\t  scope for the Pack 1 schema-only slice. Headroom preserved.\n94\t- Any per-source metadata (sender, doc URL, etc.) — corpus-card\n95\t  work; lives outside Pack 1.\n96\t\n97\tRationale for landing `created_at` now: it is the one non-\n98\tcontroversial metadata field with a deterministic write-time\n99\tsource (clock at insert), it is cheap to add to the migration,\n100\tand the alternative (a second migration in 0.7.1 to add it) costs\n101\tanother ~64 s rebuild of the 1 M-row corpus. Adds zero\n102\timplementation risk because the writer site already calls\n103\t`SystemTime::now()` for the excise-audit path (`lib.rs:2206`).\n104\t\n105\t## D3 — `kind` -> `source_type` mapping\n106\t\n107\tThe locked `source_type` vocabulary is\n108\t{`email`, `article`, `paper`, `meeting`, `note`, `todo`}\n109\t(`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137`; cardinality\n110\t\"~6\" in the ADR § 2).\n111\t\n112\tThe current writer at `commit_projection_outcomes`\n113\t(`lib.rs:2841`) receives `kind: String` from\n114\t`ProjectionOutcome::Success`. The only kind exercised by tests\n115\ttoday is `\"doc\"` (AC-013 fixture seed at\n116\t`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), a synthetic name introduced for the\n117\tperformance fixture and **not** in the locked source_type\n118\tvocabulary.\n119\t\n120\t**Decision: the locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary holds\n121\tunchanged. The synthetic test fixture kind `\"doc\"` is coerced\n122\tat the writer to `source_type = \"article\"`; the vocabulary is\n123\tnot extended.** No HITL re-open required — the lock at\n124\t`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` is honored\n125\texactly.\n126\t\n127\tMapping table (Pack 1, deterministic, total):\n128\t\n129\t| Incoming `kind` value | Resolved `source_type` |\n130\t|-----------------------|------------------------|\n131\t| `\"email\"`             | `email`                |\n132\t| `\"article\"`           | `article`              |\n133\t| `\"paper\"`             | `paper`                |\n134\t| `\"meeting\"`           | `meeting`              |\n135\t| `\"note\"`              | `note`                 |\n136\t| `\"todo\"`              | `todo`                 |\n137\t| `\"doc\"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |\n138\t| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |\n139\t\n140\tRationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds\n141\tsynthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most\n142\tsemantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked\n143\t6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key\n144\tutility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real\n145\tsource_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),\n146\t(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write\n147\t`kind=\"doc\"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)\n148\tmatches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit\n149\t`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The\n150\tcoercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is\n151\tpreserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in\n152\t`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish\n153\tfixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.\n154\t\n155\tRejected alternatives:\n156\t\n157\t- \"Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value\" — extends the\n158\t  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the\n159\t  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex\n160\t  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`\n161\t  finding 1).\n162\t- \"Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked\n163\t  values\" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture\n164\t  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).\n165\t- \"Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds\" — loses the\n166\t  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the\n167\t  \"partition_key is locked\" guarantee in HITL Q5.\n168\t\n169\tCitation: HITL lock at\n170\t`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +\n171\t\"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff\").\n172\t\n173\tThe mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:\n174\t\n175\t```rust\n176\tfn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {\n177\t    Ok(match kind {\n178\t        \"email\" => \"email\",\n179\t        \"article\" => \"article\",\n180\t        \"paper\" => \"paper\",\n181\t        \"meeting\" => \"meeting\",\n182\t        \"note\" => \"note\",\n183\t        \"todo\" => \"todo\",\n184\t        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to \"article\" so\n185\t        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.\n186\t        \"doc\" => \"article\",\n187\t        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),\n188\t    })\n189\t}\n190\t```\n191\t\n192\t(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both\n193\twriter sites in D7.)\n194\t\n195\t## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy\n196\t\n197\tvec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)\n198\tsupport neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level\n199\trule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor\n200\t`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec\n201\t`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release\n202\thistory). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate\n203\tunder the same name, with the row population rebuilt from\n204\tcanonical state via the existing rebuild driver — not the\n205\tstaging-table + RENAME shape originally drafted.\n206\t\n207\t**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The\n208\tmigration is a single writer-envelope rebuild — DROP the old\n209\t`vector_default`, CREATE it again with the new schema under the\n210\tsame name, then repopulate via the existing\n211\t`Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n212\t(`RebuildKind::Vec0`). The writer enforces non-nullability from\n213\tcommit zero.**\n214\t\n215\tSchema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration\n216\tframework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at\n217\t`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n218\t`PRAGMA user_version` (probed at `lib.rs:2071-2072` for the\n219\t`dump_schema` surface and at `lib.rs:2691` for the open-time\n220\tsanity check). The new vec0 schema lands as a new\n221\t`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing\n222\tmigration array passed into `open_with_migrations`\n223\t(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps\n224\t`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same\n225\tsentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously\n226\tproposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the\n227\tschema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows\n228\t(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.\n229\t\n230\tMigration step (Pack 1):\n231\t\n232\t```sql\n233\t-- Step body, executed by migrate_with_event_sink at lib.rs:1238.\n234\t-- Runs inside the migration framework's transaction envelope.\n235\tDROP TABLE vector_default;\n236\tCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n237\t  embedding float[<dim>],\n238\t  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n239\t  source_type TEXT partition key,\n240\t  kind TEXT,\n241\t  created_at INTEGER\n242\t);\n243\t```\n244\t\n245\tRepopulation: deliberately not done by `INSERT ... SELECT` from\n246\tthe old vec0 (the old table is dropped above and the new one\n247\thas zero rows). Instead, after the migration commits, the open\n248\tpath invokes the existing vec0 rebuild driver,\n249\t`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls\n250\t`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n251\t(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). That driver already knows how to:\n252\t\n253\t- Truncate the (newly-created, empty) `vector_default` and\n254\t  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` shadow tables (no-op on first pass\n255\t  but kept for the contract — see `lib.rs:2265-2270`).\n256\t- Re-derive rows from `canonical_nodes` via the standard\n257\t  projection pipeline, which writes through the Pack 1 writer\n258\t  in D5 and therefore lands `embedding_bin`, `source_type`,\n259\t  `kind`, `created_at` correctly on every row.\n260\t\n261\tThe whole sequence runs under the engine's existing\n262\tsingle-writer envelope: `migrate_with_event_sink` holds the\n263\twriter for the DDL step, and `run_rebuild` re-acquires the\n264\twriter transaction (`lib.rs:2257-2259`) immediately after.\n265\tThere is no window in which a reader can observe a partially\n266\trebuilt `vector_default`, because the engine does not advertise\n267\titself as open until `open_with_migrations` returns\n268\t(`lib.rs:1238-1255`).\n269\t\n270\tNOT NULL enforcement:\n271\t\n272\t- `embedding`, `embedding_bin`, `source_type`, `kind`,\n273\t  `created_at` are all written on every insert by Pack 1's\n274\t  writer; no row can land with a NULL.\n275\t- vec0 metadata columns do not have a declarative `NOT NULL`\n276\t  constraint in the sqlite-vec DDL surface\n277\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html).\n278\t  Non-nullability is therefore enforced **at the writer**, not\n279\t  by the DDL. This is a contract, not a column constraint.\n280\t- The rebuild from canonical leaves no nullable row to clean up\n281\t  later, so there is no Pack 2 \"tighten to NOT NULL\" follow-up.\n282\t\n283\tMigration cost: the rebuild scans `canonical_nodes` end-to-end\n284\tand re-runs the projection writer for each row. The comparable\n285\tbaseline is the AC-013 seed cost — 562 s on canonical CI per\n286\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`\n287\t— but the migration **does not** re-run the embedder (canonical\n288\tstate already carries the f32 embeddings via the existing vec0\n289\trestore path used by the rebuild driver), so the wall time\n290\tshould land well below 562 s on the 1 M-row fixture. The\n291\t60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate remains the working budget; the seed\n292\ttime is cited only as an upper bound. A concrete measurement\n293\tlands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.\n294\t\n295\tIdempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry. On\n296\tthe second open the migration step is skipped by\n297\t`migrate_with_event_sink`, the rebuild driver is not invoked,\n298\tand `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first pass.\n299\t\n300\t## D5 — Writer transaction shape\n301\t\n302\tThe writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at\n303\t`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**\n304\t`tx.execute` sequence between the existing\n305\t`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing\n306\t`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra\n307\tlock; no extra connection.\n308\t\n309\t**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL\n310\tstatement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**\n311\t\n312\tThe rewritten statement:\n313\t\n314\t```rust\n315\ttx.execute(\n316\t    \"INSERT OR IGNORE INTO vector_default(\n317\t        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n318\t     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n319\t    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n320\t)?;\n321\t```\n322\t\n323\tJustification (one paragraph):\n324\t\n325\tThe SQL-side shape keeps the f32 blob single-bound (one rusqlite\n326\t`Vec<u8>` allocation, one bind), lets sqlite-vec compute the\n327\tbit-vector against its own internal blob layout (which is what\n328\tthe Pack 2 reader will also see), and avoids pulling a Rust-side\n329\t`vec_quantize_binary` dependency or re-implementing the sign-bit\n330\tfold in the engine crate. The \"double-evaluation\" concern (vec0\n331\tmaterialising `?2` twice) is a non-issue because the binary\n332\tquantization is a single sequential sign-bit pass over the same\n333\tin-memory blob — both passes operate on the same bound parameter\n334\tand the SQLite parameter store does not copy. The Rust-side\n335\talternative would (a) require either linking against sqlite-vec's\n336\tC symbols from Rust or shipping a hand-rolled sign-fold, (b)\n337\tdouble the f32 footprint at bind time, and (c) couple the engine\n338\tcrate to the on-the-wire bit format which is sqlite-vec's\n339\tinternal concern. SQL-side is the cleaner contract surface.\n340\t\n341\t## D6 — `vec_quantize_binary()` contract validation plan\n342\t\n343\tThe Pack 1 RED test is a round-trip:\n344\t\n345\t1. Build a known f32 vector `v` of length `<dim>` whose sign\n346\t   pattern is hand-checkable.\n347\t2. Insert via the writer path.\n348\t3. Assert `vec_distance_hamming(embedding_bin, vec_quantize_binary(vec_f32(v))) = 0`.\n349\t\n350\tSpecified fixture (deterministic, no normalisation involved):\n351\t\n352\t```\n353\tdim = 768.\n354\tv[i] = +1.0 for i in 0..384, -1.0 for i in 384..768.\n355\t```\n356\t\n357\tExpected `embedding_bin`: 384 set bits in the leading half, 384\n358\tclear bits in the trailing half. Popcount = 384. The exact bit\n359\tordering (LSB-first within each byte vs MSB-first) is an\n360\tsqlite-vec internal contract; the round-trip via\n361\t`vec_quantize_binary` guarantees both writer and reader see the\n362\tsame packing, which is the only invariant the engine relies on.\n363\t`vec_distance_hamming` against the same vector binarised the same\n364\tway must be 0.\n365\t\n366\tOne fixture is sufficient. The previously-drafted secondary\n367\t\"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed (its claim that\n368\t`normalise([1,-1,1,-1,...])` and the half/half vector share\n369\t\"identical sign patterns at every coordinate\" is wrong — one is\n370\thalf-positive/half-negative, the other alternates — see codex\n371\tverdict finding 3). If P1-IMPL wants a second fixture for\n372\tdefence-in-depth, the recommended shape is a vector that is +1\n373\ton every fourth coordinate and -1 elsewhere\n374\t(`v3[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0` for dim=768): popcount\n375\tof the quantization is exactly 192 set bits, trivially\n376\thand-checked, and clearly distinct from the half/half fixture's\n377\tpopcount of 384.\n378\t\n379\tValidation status: **empirical validation deferred to P1-IMPL's\n380\tRED test.** A one-shot `sqlite3` confirmation against a temp DB\n381\twith `sqlite-vec` loaded was considered for this memo but\n382\trejected because (a) the Rust crate is the binding the writer\n383\tactually uses and the sqlite3 CLI binding is a separate code\n384\tpath, (b) P1-IMPL's RED test exercises the engine writer\n385\tend-to-end which is the only contract that matters, and (c) the\n386\tbinary-quant guide\n387\t(https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)\n388\talready documents the round-trip shape and `vec_distance_hamming`\n389\tbehaviour. If the RED test surfaces a contract surprise (signed\n390\tzero, NaN, byte-order), that is HITL escalation territory per\n391\tthe ADR § 6 / \"vec_quantize_binary() input expectations\" — not\n392\tsomething this design memo can resolve in advance.\n393\t\n394\tOpen-item linkage: the ADR § 6 third bullet calls out the\n395\tfixture's \"atypically friendly\" sign-pattern concentration (mass\n396\ton 6 of 768 coordinates per `tests/perf_gates.rs:317`). That is a\n397\trecall-headroom concern for Pack 2, not a contract concern for\n398\tPack 1. Pack 1's RED test is correctness, not recall.\n399\t\n400\t## D7 — Second writer site (test-only)\n401\t\n402\tConfirmed. The test-only helper at\n403\t`Engine::write_vector_for_test` (`lib.rs:1806-1845`) is a second\n404\tingest path that inserts into `vector_default` (line 1838). Pack 1\n405\tmust update this site in lockstep with `commit_projection_outcomes`\n406\tor it will violate the NOT NULL contract on `embedding_bin` /\n407\t`source_type` / `kind` / `created_at` and break every test that\n408\tgoes through `write_vector_for_test`.\n409\t\n410\tThe rewritten test helper insert is structurally identical to D5:\n411\t\n412\t```rust\n413\ttx.execute(\n414\t    \"INSERT INTO vector_default(\n415\t        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n416\t     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n417\t    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n418\t)?;\n419\t```\n420\t\n421\tPack 1 implementation MUST touch both:\n422\t\n423\t- `lib.rs:1832-1841` (test helper writer; the\n424\t  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert at :1832-1836 also needs the\n425\t  same `kind` value flow as `commit_projection_outcomes`).\n426\t- `lib.rs:2845-2852` (production writer; D5 site).\n427\t\n428\tNo other writer site touches `vector_default`. The delete sites\n429\t(`lib.rs:2177`, `:2265`) are unaffected — they target the row by\n430\trowid and the column changes are append-only at the schema level.\n431\tThe writer-loop pins at `:2174`, `:2181`, `:2242` are not touched\n432\t(they DELETE-by-rowid or operate on the shadow `_fathomdb_vector_rows`\n433\ttable, not on the metadata columns being added).\n434\t\n435\t## D8 — Reader-path NO-OP guarantee\n436\t\n437\tThe Pack 2 reader rewrite is out of scope. The Pack 1 question is:\n438\tdoes the **existing** reader at `read_search_in_tx`\n439\t(`lib.rs:2317-2323`) keep working over the migrated schema?\n440\t\n441\tThe existing query is:\n442\t\n443\t```sql\n444\tSELECT rowid FROM vector_default\n445\tWHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1)\n446\tORDER BY distance\n447\tLIMIT 10\n448\t```\n449\t\n450\t**Decision: confirmed no-op. The existing reader continues to\n451\treturn identical results post-migration.**\n452\t\n453\tReasoning:\n454\t\n455\t- The `embedding` column is **retained** (ADR § 2.1 \"the f32\n456\t  `embedding` column is retained\"). Its declared type\n457\t  `float[<dim>]` is unchanged.\n458\t- vec0's MATCH semantics dispatch on the column referenced in the\n459\t  predicate; adding sibling vector columns\n460\t  (`embedding_bin bit[<dim>]`) and metadata columns\n461\t  (`source_type`, `kind`, `created_at`) does not alter the\n462\t  semantics of `embedding MATCH vec_f32(?)`.\n463\t- The metadata + partition-key release blog\n464\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html)\n465\t  demonstrates a vec0 declaration with `partition key` + plain\n466\t  metadata columns + the vector column, queried by the vector\n467\t  predicate alone; the additional columns are filterable via\n468\t  `WHERE` but do not become mandatory in the query shape.\n469\t- The Pack 1 migration preserves the `rowid <-> write_cursor`\n470\t  identity used throughout the writer loop (`lib.rs:2174-2175`\n471\t  comment, `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`); the `INSERT INTO\n472\t  vector_default_v2 ... SELECT v.rowid` clause is explicit\n473\t  about it.\n474\t\n475\tAC-013 latency therefore stays at 2048 / 2327 ms post-Pack 1\n476\t(matches the ADR § 4 / handoff § 1 stated contract). AC-019\n477\tstays at its existing bound. AC-012 / AC-017 / AC-018 / AC-020\n478\tare untouched because they do not query `vector_default`.\n479\t\n480\t## Open escalations\n481\t\n482\tNone. All eight decisions resolved against repo + cited external\n483\tdocs. The pre-existing open items in the ADR § 6 (\"final numeric\n484\tbudgets\", \"K-value selection\", \"fixture-friendliness for recall\")\n485\tare Pack 2 concerns and are not affected by Pack 1.\n486\t\n487\t## Fix-1 changelog\n488\t\n489\tAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n490\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n491\t\n492\t- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n493\t  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n494\t  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n495\t  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n496\t  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n497\t  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n498\t  list updated in D3.\n499\t- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n500\t  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n501\t  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n502\t  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n503\t  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n504\t  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n505\t  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`), with repopulation through the existing\n506\t  `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n507\t  (`RebuildKind::Vec0`, `lib.rs:1947` and `lib.rs:2234-2289`).\n508\t  The fabricated `operational_mutations` schema stamp is\n509\t  removed. Cost baseline is the AC-013 562 s seed time\n510\t  (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`),\n511\t  with the rebuild expected materially under that since the\n512\t  embedder does not re-run.\n513\t- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n514\t  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n515\t  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n516\t  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n517\t  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n518\t  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n519\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9bc34b42-72f6-4ea4-bdb1-fbe5438de144","uuid":"bebee06b-26e1-4d5b-96aa-568e486f2137","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:45:45.276Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/design/0.7.0-vector-quant-pack1.md","content":"---\ntitle: 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\ndate: 2026-05-27\ntarget_release: 0.7.0\ndesc: Pack 1 schema-migration + ingest double-write decisions for\n  the binary-quantization data-encoding change locked by\n  ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md.\nblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (schema +\n  writer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs\n  (existing fixture continuity); dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md\n  (implements its Pack 1 section).\nstatus: draft fix-1 (consumed by Pack 1 implementation)\n---\n\n# 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n\nThis memo resolves the open design questions called out in\n`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md` § \"Pack 1\"\nand § \"Open items the implementing agent should escalate to HITL\"\nso that Pack 1 implementation can land mechanically. Pairs with\nADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md (which records the *what*); this\nmemo records the *exact shape*.\n\nScope: Pack 1 only — schema migration + writer double-write. No\nreader changes. The Pack 2 query rewrite is out of scope for this\nmemo and is owned by a separate design pass when Pack 2 starts.\n\n## D1 — Sibling column vs. sibling table\n\n**Decision: sibling column on `vector_default`.**\n\nThe migrated declaration is:\n\n```\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n```\n\n(`<dim>` = 768 for the current default profile; the existing\n`ensure_vector_partition` builds the dimension from\n`load_default_profile` at `lib.rs:3278-3283`.)\n\n- Alternatives weighed: sibling table `vector_default_bin` (one\n  extra join on every read; fan-out cost on the Pack 2 reader; two\n  inserts per row instead of one; two DELETE sites in every\n  excise / rebuild path — `lib.rs:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`).\n- Citation: the sqlite-vec binary-quant guide demonstrates the\n  exact mixed-flavour declaration\n  `create virtual table vec_movies using vec0(synopsis_embedding\n  float[768], synopsis_embedding_coarse bit[768])`\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html);\n  confirmed empirically by WebFetch on 2026-05-27 against the\n  same page.\n\nThe sibling-column shape is the default in the handoff\n(§ 1.1) and in the ADR (§ 2 / Pack 1.1). The sibling-table\nfallback remains documented in both as a recovery path **only if**\nthe 16-metadata-column cap is exceeded (see D2) — that is not the\ncase for Pack 1.\n\n## D2 — Metadata column inventory (vec0 16-col cap)\n\nvec0 caps metadata columns at 16 and partition keys at 4\n(`dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md:70-71`). The Pack 1\nschema lands the minimum-viable set with headroom for the\nreal-workload extension already foreseen by the ADR and the\nHITL doc.\n\nPack 1 column inventory on `vector_default`:\n\n| # | Column            | Type           | Role                  | Source                                                         |\n|---|-------------------|----------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n| 0 | `rowid`           | INTEGER        | (implicit pk)         | `cursor` (existing — `lib.rs:2845-2851`).                      |\n| 1 | `embedding`       | `float[<dim>]` | vector                | existing — `vec_quantize_binary` input + Pack 2 rerank.        |\n| 2 | `embedding_bin`   | `bit[<dim>]`   | quantized vector      | `vec_quantize_binary(embedding)` at write time.                |\n| 3 | `source_type`     | `TEXT`         | **partition key**     | derived from `kind` per D3.                                    |\n| 4 | `kind`            | `TEXT`         | metadata col          | existing `ProjectionOutcome::Success.kind` (`lib.rs:2841`).    |\n| 5 | `created_at`      | `INTEGER`     | metadata col          | UNIX seconds at write time (mirrors `excised_at` pattern at `lib.rs:2206`). |\n\nHeadroom: **11 free metadata column slots + 3 free partition-key\nslots** after Pack 1.\n\nDeferred to Pack 2 / 0.7.1 (NOT landed in Pack 1):\n\n- `tags`, `project_mentions` — named in the handoff § 1.1 but not\n  populated by today's writer; the chunk record carries no such\n  field. Wiring requires upstream code changes that are out of\n  scope for the Pack 1 schema-only slice. Headroom preserved.\n- Any per-source metadata (sender, doc URL, etc.) — corpus-card\n  work; lives outside Pack 1.\n\nRationale for landing `created_at` now: it is the one non-\ncontroversial metadata field with a deterministic write-time\nsource (clock at insert), it is cheap to add to the migration,\nand the alternative (a second migration in 0.7.1 to add it) costs\nanother ~64 s rebuild of the 1 M-row corpus. Adds zero\nimplementation risk because the writer site already calls\n`SystemTime::now()` for the excise-audit path (`lib.rs:2206`).\n\n## D3 — `kind` -> `source_type` mapping\n\nThe locked `source_type` vocabulary is\n{`email`, `article`, `paper`, `meeting`, `note`, `todo`}\n(`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137`; cardinality\n\"~6\" in the ADR § 2).\n\nThe current writer at `commit_projection_outcomes`\n(`lib.rs:2841`) receives `kind: String` from\n`ProjectionOutcome::Success`. The only kind exercised by tests\ntoday is `\"doc\"` (AC-013 fixture seed at\n`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), a synthetic name introduced for the\nperformance fixture and **not** in the locked source_type\nvocabulary.\n\n**Decision: the locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary holds\nunchanged. The synthetic test fixture kind `\"doc\"` is coerced\nat the writer to `source_type = \"article\"`; the vocabulary is\nnot extended.** No HITL re-open required — the lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` is honored\nexactly.\n\nMapping table (Pack 1, deterministic, total):\n\n| Incoming `kind` value | Resolved `source_type` |\n|-----------------------|------------------------|\n| `\"email\"`             | `email`                |\n| `\"article\"`           | `article`              |\n| `\"paper\"`             | `paper`                |\n| `\"meeting\"`           | `meeting`              |\n| `\"note\"`              | `note`                 |\n| `\"todo\"`              | `todo`                 |\n| `\"doc\"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |\n| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |\n\nRationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds\nsynthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most\nsemantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked\n6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key\nutility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real\nsource_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),\n(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write\n`kind=\"doc\"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)\nmatches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit\n`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The\ncoercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is\npreserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish\nfixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.\n\nRejected alternatives:\n\n- \"Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value\" — extends the\n  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the\n  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex\n  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`\n  finding 1).\n- \"Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked\n  values\" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture\n  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).\n- \"Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds\" — loses the\n  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the\n  \"partition_key is locked\" guarantee in HITL Q5.\n\nCitation: HITL lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +\n\"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff\").\n\nThe mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:\n\n```rust\nfn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {\n    Ok(match kind {\n        \"email\" => \"email\",\n        \"article\" => \"article\",\n        \"paper\" => \"paper\",\n        \"meeting\" => \"meeting\",\n        \"note\" => \"note\",\n        \"todo\" => \"todo\",\n        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to \"article\" so\n        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.\n        \"doc\" => \"article\",\n        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),\n    })\n}\n```\n\n(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both\nwriter sites in D7.)\n\n## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy\n\nvec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)\nsupport neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level\nrule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor\n`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec\n`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release\nhistory). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate\nunder the same name, with the row population rebuilt from\ncanonical state via the existing rebuild driver — not the\nstaging-table + RENAME shape originally drafted.\n\n**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The\nmigration is a single writer-envelope rebuild — DROP the old\n`vector_default`, CREATE it again with the new schema under the\nsame name, then repopulate via the existing\n`Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n(`RebuildKind::Vec0`). The writer enforces non-nullability from\ncommit zero.**\n\nSchema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration\nframework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at\n`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n`PRAGMA user_version` (probed at `lib.rs:2071-2072` for the\n`dump_schema` surface and at `lib.rs:2691` for the open-time\nsanity check). The new vec0 schema lands as a new\n`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing\nmigration array passed into `open_with_migrations`\n(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps\n`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same\nsentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously\nproposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the\nschema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows\n(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.\n\nMigration step (Pack 1):\n\n```sql\n-- Step body, executed by migrate_with_event_sink at lib.rs:1238.\n-- Runs inside the migration framework's transaction envelope.\nDROP TABLE vector_default;\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n```\n\nRepopulation: deliberately not done by `INSERT ... SELECT` from\nthe old vec0 (the old table is dropped above and the new one\nhas zero rows). Instead, after the migration commits, the open\npath invokes the existing vec0 rebuild driver,\n`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls\n`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). That driver already knows how to:\n\n- Truncate the (newly-created, empty) `vector_default` and\n  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` shadow tables (no-op on first pass\n  but kept for the contract — see `lib.rs:2265-2270`).\n- Re-derive rows from `canonical_nodes` via the standard\n  projection pipeline, which writes through the Pack 1 writer\n  in D5 and therefore lands `embedding_bin`, `source_type`,\n  `kind`, `created_at` correctly on every row.\n\nThe whole sequence runs under the engine's existing\nsingle-writer envelope: `migrate_with_event_sink` holds the\nwriter for the DDL step, and `run_rebuild` re-acquires the\nwriter transaction (`lib.rs:2257-2259`) immediately after.\nThere is no window in which a reader can observe a partially\nrebuilt `vector_default`, because the engine does not advertise\nitself as open until `open_with_migrations` returns\n(`lib.rs:1238-1255`).\n\nNOT NULL enforcement:\n\n- `embedding`, `embedding_bin`, `source_type`, `kind`,\n  `created_at` are all written on every insert by Pack 1's\n  writer; no row can land with a NULL.\n- vec0 metadata columns do not have a declarative `NOT NULL`\n  constraint in the sqlite-vec DDL surface\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html).\n  Non-nullability is therefore enforced **at the writer**, not\n  by the DDL. This is a contract, not a column constraint.\n- The rebuild from canonical leaves no nullable row to clean up\n  later, so there is no Pack 2 \"tighten to NOT NULL\" follow-up.\n\nMigration cost: the rebuild scans `canonical_nodes` end-to-end\nand re-runs the projection writer for each row. The comparable\nbaseline is the AC-013 seed cost — 562 s on canonical CI per\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`\n— but the migration **does not** re-run the embedder (canonical\nstate already carries the f32 embeddings via the existing vec0\nrestore path used by the rebuild driver), so the wall time\nshould land well below 562 s on the 1 M-row fixture. The\n60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate remains the working budget; the seed\ntime is cited only as an upper bound. A concrete measurement\nlands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.\n\nIdempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry. On\nthe second open the migration step is skipped by\n`migrate_with_event_sink`, the rebuild driver is not invoked,\nand `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first pass.\n\n## D5 — Writer transaction shape\n\nThe writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at\n`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**\n`tx.execute` sequence between the existing\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing\n`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra\nlock; no extra connection.\n\n**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL\nstatement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**\n\nThe rewritten statement:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT OR IGNORE INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nJustification (one paragraph):\n\nThe SQL-side shape keeps the f32 blob single-bound (one rusqlite\n`Vec<u8>` allocation, one bind), lets sqlite-vec compute the\nbit-vector against its own internal blob layout (which is what\nthe Pack 2 reader will also see), and avoids pulling a Rust-side\n`vec_quantize_binary` dependency or re-implementing the sign-bit\nfold in the engine crate. The \"double-evaluation\" concern (vec0\nmaterialising `?2` twice) is a non-issue because the binary\nquantization is a single sequential sign-bit pass over the same\nin-memory blob — both passes operate on the same bound parameter\nand the SQLite parameter store does not copy. The Rust-side\nalternative would (a) require either linking against sqlite-vec's\nC symbols from Rust or shipping a hand-rolled sign-fold, (b)\ndouble the f32 footprint at bind time, and (c) couple the engine\ncrate to the on-the-wire bit format which is sqlite-vec's\ninternal concern. SQL-side is the cleaner contract surface.\n\n## D6 — `vec_quantize_binary()` contract validation plan\n\nThe Pack 1 RED test is a round-trip:\n\n1. Build a known f32 vector `v` of length `<dim>` whose sign\n   pattern is hand-checkable.\n2. Insert via the writer path.\n3. Assert `vec_distance_hamming(embedding_bin, vec_quantize_binary(vec_f32(v))) = 0`.\n\nSpecified fixture (deterministic, no normalisation involved):\n\n```\ndim = 768.\nv[i] = +1.0 for i in 0..384, -1.0 for i in 384..768.\n```\n\nExpected `embedding_bin`: 384 set bits in the leading half, 384\nclear bits in the trailing half. Popcount = 384. The exact bit\nordering (LSB-first within each byte vs MSB-first) is an\nsqlite-vec internal contract; the round-trip via\n`vec_quantize_binary` guarantees both writer and reader see the\nsame packing, which is the only invariant the engine relies on.\n`vec_distance_hamming` against the same vector binarised the same\nway must be 0.\n\nOne fixture is sufficient. The previously-drafted secondary\n\"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed (its claim that\n`normalise([1,-1,1,-1,...])` and the half/half vector share\n\"identical sign patterns at every coordinate\" is wrong — one is\nhalf-positive/half-negative, the other alternates — see codex\nverdict finding 3). If P1-IMPL wants a second fixture for\ndefence-in-depth, the recommended shape is a vector that is +1\non every fourth coordinate and -1 elsewhere\n(`v3[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0` for dim=768): popcount\nof the quantization is exactly 192 set bits, trivially\nhand-checked, and clearly distinct from the half/half fixture's\npopcount of 384.\n\nValidation status: **empirical validation deferred to P1-IMPL's\nRED test.** A one-shot `sqlite3` confirmation against a temp DB\nwith `sqlite-vec` loaded was considered for this memo but\nrejected because (a) the Rust crate is the binding the writer\nactually uses and the sqlite3 CLI binding is a separate code\npath, (b) P1-IMPL's RED test exercises the engine writer\nend-to-end which is the only contract that matters, and (c) the\nbinary-quant guide\n(https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)\nalready documents the round-trip shape and `vec_distance_hamming`\nbehaviour. If the RED test surfaces a contract surprise (signed\nzero, NaN, byte-order), that is HITL escalation territory per\nthe ADR § 6 / \"vec_quantize_binary() input expectations\" — not\nsomething this design memo can resolve in advance.\n\nOpen-item linkage: the ADR § 6 third bullet calls out the\nfixture's \"atypically friendly\" sign-pattern concentration (mass\non 6 of 768 coordinates per `tests/perf_gates.rs:317`). That is a\nrecall-headroom concern for Pack 2, not a contract concern for\nPack 1. Pack 1's RED test is correctness, not recall.\n\n## D7 — Second writer site (test-only)\n\nConfirmed. The test-only helper at\n`Engine::write_vector_for_test` (`lib.rs:1806-1845`) is a second\ningest path that inserts into `vector_default` (line 1838). Pack 1\nmust update this site in lockstep with `commit_projection_outcomes`\nor it will violate the NOT NULL contract on `embedding_bin` /\n`source_type` / `kind` / `created_at` and break every test that\ngoes through `write_vector_for_test`.\n\nThe rewritten test helper insert is structurally identical to D5:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nPack 1 implementation MUST touch both:\n\n- `lib.rs:1832-1841` (test helper writer; the\n  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert at :1832-1836 also needs the\n  same `kind` value flow as `commit_projection_outcomes`).\n- `lib.rs:2845-2852` (production writer; D5 site).\n\nNo other writer site touches `vector_default`. The delete sites\n(`lib.rs:2177`, `:2265`) are unaffected — they target the row by\nrowid and the column changes are append-only at the schema level.\nThe writer-loop pins at `:2174`, `:2181`, `:2242` are not touched\n(they DELETE-by-rowid or operate on the shadow `_fathomdb_vector_rows`\ntable, not on the metadata columns being added).\n\n## D8 — Reader-path NO-OP guarantee\n\nThe Pack 2 reader rewrite is out of scope. The Pack 1 question is:\ndoes the **existing** reader at `read_search_in_tx`\n(`lib.rs:2317-2323`) keep working over the migrated schema?\n\nThe existing query is:\n\n```sql\nSELECT rowid FROM vector_default\nWHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1)\nORDER BY distance\nLIMIT 10\n```\n\n**Decision: confirmed no-op. The existing reader continues to\nreturn identical results post-migration.**\n\nReasoning:\n\n- The `embedding` column is **retained** (ADR § 2.1 \"the f32\n  `embedding` column is retained\"). Its declared type\n  `float[<dim>]` is unchanged.\n- vec0's MATCH semantics dispatch on the column referenced in the\n  predicate; adding sibling vector columns\n  (`embedding_bin bit[<dim>]`) and metadata columns\n  (`source_type`, `kind`, `created_at`) does not alter the\n  semantics of `embedding MATCH vec_f32(?)`.\n- The metadata + partition-key release blog\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html)\n  demonstrates a vec0 declaration with `partition key` + plain\n  metadata columns + the vector column, queried by the vector\n  predicate alone; the additional columns are filterable via\n  `WHERE` but do not become mandatory in the query shape.\n- The Pack 1 migration preserves the `rowid <-> write_cursor`\n  identity used throughout the writer loop (`lib.rs:2174-2175`\n  comment, `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`); the `INSERT INTO\n  vector_default_v2 ... SELECT v.rowid` clause is explicit\n  about it.\n\nAC-013 latency therefore stays at 2048 / 2327 ms post-Pack 1\n(matches the ADR § 4 / handoff § 1 stated contract). AC-019\nstays at its existing bound. AC-012 / AC-017 / AC-018 / AC-020\nare untouched because they do not query `vector_default`.\n\n## Open escalations\n\nNone. All eight decisions resolved against repo + cited external\ndocs. The pre-existing open items in the ADR § 6 (\"final numeric\nbudgets\", \"K-value selection\", \"fixture-friendliness for recall\")\nare Pack 2 concerns and are not affected by Pack 1.\n\n## Fix-1 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n\n- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n  list updated in D3.\n- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`), with repopulation through the existing\n  `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n  (`RebuildKind::Vec0`, `lib.rs:1947` and `lib.rs:2234-2289`).\n  The fabricated `operational_mutations` schema stamp is\n  removed. Cost baseline is the AC-013 562 s seed time\n  (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`),\n  with the rebuild expected materially under that since the\n  embedder does not re-run.\n- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n","numLines":519,"startLine":1,"totalLines":519}}}
