{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Awj3oDcmt57GepAtecPRAN","type":"tool_result","content":"The file /tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/design/0.7.0-vector-quant-pack1.md has been updated successfully. (file state is current in your context — no need to Read it back)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9bc34b42-72f6-4ea4-bdb1-fbe5438de144","uuid":"a9c86e9d-54a6-4de0-b16d-cc8c97301d24","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:48:15.814Z","tool_use_result":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/design/0.7.0-vector-quant-pack1.md","oldString":"## Fix-1 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n\n- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n  list updated in D3.\n- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`), with repopulation through the existing\n  `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n  (`RebuildKind::Vec0`, `lib.rs:1947` and `lib.rs:2234-2289`).\n  The fabricated `operational_mutations` schema stamp is\n  removed. Cost baseline is the AC-013 562 s seed time\n  (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`),\n  with the rebuild expected materially under that since the\n  embedder does not re-run.\n- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.","newString":"## Fix-1 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n\n- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n  list updated in D3.\n- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`). (Repopulation shape later replaced by\n  the fix-2 staged copy; see Fix-2 changelog below.)\n- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n\n## Fix-2 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`\n(one new high finding on D4's repopulation semantics).\n\n- **Fix 2.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4 repopulation no\n  longer routes through `Engine::rebuild_vec0` /\n  `rebuild_shadow_state` (`RebuildKind::Vec0`). Verified against\n  the actual code: `run_projection_job` at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2523-2557` calls\n  `embedder.embed(&job.body)` per row, and the rebuild test at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n  locks in async drain semantics — both contradict the fix-1\n  claim that repopulation is synchronous and avoids the\n  embedder. D4 is replaced with a single SQL migration step\n  executed under `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`,\n  re-verified): (1) stage existing `vector_default` rows\n  JOIN-ed with `_fathomdb_vector_rows.kind` into a regular\n  staging table, (2) `DROP TABLE vector_default` + recreate\n  with the Pack 1 schema, (3) `INSERT ... SELECT` from staging\n  with `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side and a CASE expression\n  rendering the D3 `kind -> source_type` map, (4) drop the\n  staging table. Properties recorded explicitly: synchronous,\n  no embedder rerun, atomic under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`/`COMMIT`,\n  `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side once per row. Cost citation\n  updated: the AC-013 562 s seed figure is no longer cited as\n  a baseline because it includes embedder work this migration\n  avoids; budget remains the 60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate. A\n  \"Rejected alternative\" subsection added under D4 explaining\n  why `rebuild_vec0` is not used.\n- **Fix 2.2 (consequence).** D4 SQL-only migration shape is\n  justified against the actual `Migration { step_id: u32, sql:\n  &'static str }` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`\n  (re-verified) — pure SQL, no Rust callback extension point.\n  CASE WHEN is the migration-time mirror of the D3 helper\n  `resolve_source_type`; P1-IMPL is directed to add a\n  co-located drift-detection assertion.","originalFile":"---\ntitle: 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\ndate: 2026-05-27\ntarget_release: 0.7.0\ndesc: Pack 1 schema-migration + ingest double-write decisions for\n  the binary-quantization data-encoding change locked by\n  ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md.\nblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (schema +\n  writer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs\n  (existing fixture continuity); dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md\n  (implements its Pack 1 section).\nstatus: draft fix-2 (consumed by Pack 1 implementation)\n---\n\n# 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n\nThis memo resolves the open design questions called out in\n`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md` § \"Pack 1\"\nand § \"Open items the implementing agent should escalate to HITL\"\nso that Pack 1 implementation can land mechanically. Pairs with\nADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md (which records the *what*); this\nmemo records the *exact shape*.\n\nScope: Pack 1 only — schema migration + writer double-write. No\nreader changes. The Pack 2 query rewrite is out of scope for this\nmemo and is owned by a separate design pass when Pack 2 starts.\n\n## D1 — Sibling column vs. sibling table\n\n**Decision: sibling column on `vector_default`.**\n\nThe migrated declaration is:\n\n```\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n```\n\n(`<dim>` = 768 for the current default profile; the existing\n`ensure_vector_partition` builds the dimension from\n`load_default_profile` at `lib.rs:3278-3283`.)\n\n- Alternatives weighed: sibling table `vector_default_bin` (one\n  extra join on every read; fan-out cost on the Pack 2 reader; two\n  inserts per row instead of one; two DELETE sites in every\n  excise / rebuild path — `lib.rs:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`).\n- Citation: the sqlite-vec binary-quant guide demonstrates the\n  exact mixed-flavour declaration\n  `create virtual table vec_movies using vec0(synopsis_embedding\n  float[768], synopsis_embedding_coarse bit[768])`\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html);\n  confirmed empirically by WebFetch on 2026-05-27 against the\n  same page.\n\nThe sibling-column shape is the default in the handoff\n(§ 1.1) and in the ADR (§ 2 / Pack 1.1). The sibling-table\nfallback remains documented in both as a recovery path **only if**\nthe 16-metadata-column cap is exceeded (see D2) — that is not the\ncase for Pack 1.\n\n## D2 — Metadata column inventory (vec0 16-col cap)\n\nvec0 caps metadata columns at 16 and partition keys at 4\n(`dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md:70-71`). The Pack 1\nschema lands the minimum-viable set with headroom for the\nreal-workload extension already foreseen by the ADR and the\nHITL doc.\n\nPack 1 column inventory on `vector_default`:\n\n| # | Column            | Type           | Role                  | Source                                                         |\n|---|-------------------|----------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n| 0 | `rowid`           | INTEGER        | (implicit pk)         | `cursor` (existing — `lib.rs:2845-2851`).                      |\n| 1 | `embedding`       | `float[<dim>]` | vector                | existing — `vec_quantize_binary` input + Pack 2 rerank.        |\n| 2 | `embedding_bin`   | `bit[<dim>]`   | quantized vector      | `vec_quantize_binary(embedding)` at write time.                |\n| 3 | `source_type`     | `TEXT`         | **partition key**     | derived from `kind` per D3.                                    |\n| 4 | `kind`            | `TEXT`         | metadata col          | existing `ProjectionOutcome::Success.kind` (`lib.rs:2841`).    |\n| 5 | `created_at`      | `INTEGER`     | metadata col          | UNIX seconds at write time (mirrors `excised_at` pattern at `lib.rs:2206`). |\n\nHeadroom: **11 free metadata column slots + 3 free partition-key\nslots** after Pack 1.\n\nDeferred to Pack 2 / 0.7.1 (NOT landed in Pack 1):\n\n- `tags`, `project_mentions` — named in the handoff § 1.1 but not\n  populated by today's writer; the chunk record carries no such\n  field. Wiring requires upstream code changes that are out of\n  scope for the Pack 1 schema-only slice. Headroom preserved.\n- Any per-source metadata (sender, doc URL, etc.) — corpus-card\n  work; lives outside Pack 1.\n\nRationale for landing `created_at` now: it is the one non-\ncontroversial metadata field with a deterministic write-time\nsource (clock at insert), it is cheap to add to the migration,\nand the alternative (a second migration in 0.7.1 to add it) costs\nanother ~64 s rebuild of the 1 M-row corpus. Adds zero\nimplementation risk because the writer site already calls\n`SystemTime::now()` for the excise-audit path (`lib.rs:2206`).\n\n## D3 — `kind` -> `source_type` mapping\n\nThe locked `source_type` vocabulary is\n{`email`, `article`, `paper`, `meeting`, `note`, `todo`}\n(`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137`; cardinality\n\"~6\" in the ADR § 2).\n\nThe current writer at `commit_projection_outcomes`\n(`lib.rs:2841`) receives `kind: String` from\n`ProjectionOutcome::Success`. The only kind exercised by tests\ntoday is `\"doc\"` (AC-013 fixture seed at\n`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), a synthetic name introduced for the\nperformance fixture and **not** in the locked source_type\nvocabulary.\n\n**Decision: the locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary holds\nunchanged. The synthetic test fixture kind `\"doc\"` is coerced\nat the writer to `source_type = \"article\"`; the vocabulary is\nnot extended.** No HITL re-open required — the lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` is honored\nexactly.\n\nMapping table (Pack 1, deterministic, total):\n\n| Incoming `kind` value | Resolved `source_type` |\n|-----------------------|------------------------|\n| `\"email\"`             | `email`                |\n| `\"article\"`           | `article`              |\n| `\"paper\"`             | `paper`                |\n| `\"meeting\"`           | `meeting`              |\n| `\"note\"`              | `note`                 |\n| `\"todo\"`              | `todo`                 |\n| `\"doc\"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |\n| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |\n\nRationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds\nsynthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most\nsemantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked\n6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key\nutility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real\nsource_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),\n(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write\n`kind=\"doc\"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)\nmatches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit\n`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The\ncoercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is\npreserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish\nfixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.\n\nRejected alternatives:\n\n- \"Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value\" — extends the\n  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the\n  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex\n  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`\n  finding 1).\n- \"Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked\n  values\" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture\n  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).\n- \"Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds\" — loses the\n  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the\n  \"partition_key is locked\" guarantee in HITL Q5.\n\nCitation: HITL lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +\n\"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff\").\n\nThe mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:\n\n```rust\nfn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {\n    Ok(match kind {\n        \"email\" => \"email\",\n        \"article\" => \"article\",\n        \"paper\" => \"paper\",\n        \"meeting\" => \"meeting\",\n        \"note\" => \"note\",\n        \"todo\" => \"todo\",\n        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to \"article\" so\n        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.\n        \"doc\" => \"article\",\n        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),\n    })\n}\n```\n\n(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both\nwriter sites in D7.)\n\n## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy\n\nvec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)\nsupport neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level\nrule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor\n`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec\n`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release\nhistory). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate\nunder the same name. Repopulation must be **synchronous and\nin-transaction**, copying the existing f32 blobs verbatim — it\nmust NOT go through the engine's async rebuild driver.\n\n**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The\nmigration is a single SQL migration step that (a) stages the\nexisting f32 rows + kind into a regular SQL table, (b) drops\nand recreates `vector_default` with the new schema under the\nsame name, (c) repopulates `vector_default` from the staging\ntable with `vec_quantize_binary` evaluated SQL-side at INSERT\nbind, and (d) drops the staging table — all inside the migration\nframework's `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT` envelope. The writer\nenforces non-nullability from commit zero.**\n\nSchema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration\nframework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at\n`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, which is a\nthin re-export of `fathomdb_schema::migrate_with_event_sink`\nimplemented at `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:218-271`.\n`apply_one` (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`)\nwraps each migration step in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT`,\ncalling `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` followed by\n`pragma_update(PRAGMA_USER_VERSION, step_id)`, and rolling back\non any error. `Migration` itself is `{ step_id: u32, sql:\n&'static str }` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`) — pure SQL,\nno Rust callback hook. The new vec0 schema lands as a new\n`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing\nmigration array passed into `open_with_migrations`\n(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps\n`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same\nsentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously\nproposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the\nschema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows\n(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.\n\nMigration step (Pack 1) — single SQL blob, executed atomically\nby `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`):\n\n```sql\n-- Step body. Runs inside BEGIN IMMEDIATE ... COMMIT supplied\n-- by apply_one. <dim> is rendered at migration-build time\n-- (768 for the default profile, see ensure_vector_partition at\n-- lib.rs:3278-3283). <now> is the migration timestamp (UNIX\n-- seconds), rendered by the engine when the migration array is\n-- constructed at open_with_migrations (lib.rs:1119-1131); the\n-- whole corpus is backfilled with the same created_at value.\n\n-- 1. Stage existing f32 blobs + kind into a regular SQL table.\n--    _fathomdb_vector_rows.kind is the source of truth for the\n--    existing rows' kind (writer site at lib.rs:2845-2853).\nCREATE TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 (\n  rowid     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  embedding BLOB NOT NULL,\n  kind      TEXT NOT NULL\n);\nINSERT INTO _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0(rowid, embedding, kind)\nSELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind\n  FROM vector_default v\n  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid;\n\n-- 2. Drop the old vec0 table and recreate under the same name.\nDROP TABLE vector_default;\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n\n-- 3. Repopulate from staging. vec_quantize_binary runs SQL-side\n--    once per row against the existing f32 blob; source_type is\n--    coerced from kind via the D3 mapping using a CASE\n--    expression. Any kind outside the D3 vocabulary raises\n--    SQLITE_CONSTRAINT (NOT NULL) on source_type, which aborts\n--    the migration and rolls back the whole step — matching the\n--    \"writer error on unknown kind\" rule in D3.\nINSERT INTO vector_default(\n  rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n)\nSELECT\n  s.rowid,\n  s.embedding,\n  vec_quantize_binary(s.embedding),\n  CASE s.kind\n    WHEN 'email'   THEN 'email'\n    WHEN 'article' THEN 'article'\n    WHEN 'paper'   THEN 'paper'\n    WHEN 'meeting' THEN 'meeting'\n    WHEN 'note'    THEN 'note'\n    WHEN 'todo'    THEN 'todo'\n    WHEN 'doc'     THEN 'article'  -- AC-013 fixture coercion; see D3.\n    ELSE NULL\n  END AS source_type,\n  s.kind,\n  <now>\nFROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s;\n\n-- 4. Drop the staging table.\nDROP TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0;\n```\n\nWhy the D3 mapping is inlined in SQL (and not a Rust loop): the\n`Migration` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54` is\n`{ step_id, sql: &'static str }` — pure SQL, no Rust callback\nextension point. The CASE WHEN above is the literal byte-for-byte\ntranscription of the D3 mapping table; a Rust-side loop would\nrequire extending the schema crate's migration trait (a\nlarger-blast-radius change that this slice does not authorize).\nThe CASE shape also avoids registering an ad-hoc Rust scalar\nfunction on the migration connection. The D3 helper\n`resolve_source_type` (defined in this memo for the writer\nsites D5/D7) is the canonical lookup at write time; the CASE\nabove is the migration-time mirror of that table and must be\nkept in lockstep with it — P1-IMPL adds a co-located assertion\nin tests/migration coverage to catch drift.\n\nProperties of this migration step:\n\n- **Synchronous.** All four sub-steps run inside the same\n  `apply_one` transaction (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`),\n  on the migration thread, before `migrate_with_event_sink`\n  returns. There is no async hand-off.\n- **No embedder rerun.** The f32 blobs are copied verbatim from\n  `vector_default.embedding` into the staging table and back\n  out. The embedder is never invoked.\n- **`vec_quantize_binary` call site.** SQL-side at the\n  repopulation `INSERT`'s SELECT projection, once per row,\n  evaluated against the f32 blob already materialised in the\n  staging row. No Rust-side bit math; no double scan of the\n  source blob.\n- **Atomicity.** `apply_one` wraps the whole SQL blob in\n  `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT` and `ROLLBACK`s on any error\n  (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`). If any sub-step\n  fails (e.g. an unmapped `kind` value triggers the NULL ->\n  NOT-NULL constraint at sub-step 3), the migration is rolled\n  back, `PRAGMA user_version` stays at the previous value, and\n  the next open re-attempts the migration cleanly. The staging\n  table is part of the same transaction and is dropped on\n  rollback alongside the would-be new `vector_default`.\n- **NOT NULL enforcement at write time.** vec0 metadata columns\n  do not have a declarative `NOT NULL` constraint in the\n  sqlite-vec DDL surface\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n  non-nullability is contract-enforced by the migration and by\n  the D5/D7 writers. Pack 1 writers always supply all five\n  metadata columns; the migration always supplies them (or\n  fails atomically). No row can land with a NULL.\n\nMigration cost: dominated by two sequential scans of the\nexisting 3 GB f32 corpus on the 1 M-row fixture — one for the\nstaging `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 1) and one for the\nrepopulation `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 3). The\n`vec_quantize_binary` work is a sign-bit fold per coordinate,\nnegligible relative to the I/O. The working budget remains the\n60-90 s estimate from ADR § 4. The migration **does not** re-run\nthe embedder, so the AC-013 562 s seed time\n(`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`)\nis **not** a comparable baseline — that figure includes embedder\nwork this migration avoids by construction. A concrete\nmeasurement lands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.\n\nIdempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry\n(`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:234`, `:277`). On the second open\nthe migration step is skipped because `migration.step_id <=\nbefore`, and `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first\npass.\n\n### Rejected alternative — repopulate via `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n\nThe fix-1 draft of D4 proposed driving repopulation through\n`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls\n`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). Codex fix-1 review (finding 1,\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`)\ncorrectly flagged that this path:\n\n- Is asynchronous. `rebuild_shadow_state` only truncates vec0\n  state and resets the projection cursor; the actual\n  re-derivation runs on the projection scheduler. The test at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n  observes `rebuild_vec0` returns immediately and polls\n  `projection_status_for_test` to wait for the async drain.\n- Re-runs the embedder. The projection scheduler's\n  `run_projection_job` calls `embedder.embed(&job.body)` at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2528-2557` for\n  every row it re-derives.\n- Is therefore not equivalent to copying the existing f32\n  blobs: it would multiply the migration cost by the embedder\n  work the migration is specifically designed to avoid, and it\n  would leak a window in which `vector_default` is empty before\n  the async drain catches up.\n\nThe staged-copy migration above replaces this path entirely.\n`rebuild_vec0` remains as it is in tree for the operator-driven\n\"rebuild from canonical\" tool; Pack 1's migration does not call\nit.\n\n## D5 — Writer transaction shape\n\nThe writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at\n`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**\n`tx.execute` sequence between the existing\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing\n`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra\nlock; no extra connection.\n\n**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL\nstatement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**\n\nThe rewritten statement:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT OR IGNORE INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nJustification (one paragraph):\n\nThe SQL-side shape keeps the f32 blob single-bound (one rusqlite\n`Vec<u8>` allocation, one bind), lets sqlite-vec compute the\nbit-vector against its own internal blob layout (which is what\nthe Pack 2 reader will also see), and avoids pulling a Rust-side\n`vec_quantize_binary` dependency or re-implementing the sign-bit\nfold in the engine crate. The \"double-evaluation\" concern (vec0\nmaterialising `?2` twice) is a non-issue because the binary\nquantization is a single sequential sign-bit pass over the same\nin-memory blob — both passes operate on the same bound parameter\nand the SQLite parameter store does not copy. The Rust-side\nalternative would (a) require either linking against sqlite-vec's\nC symbols from Rust or shipping a hand-rolled sign-fold, (b)\ndouble the f32 footprint at bind time, and (c) couple the engine\ncrate to the on-the-wire bit format which is sqlite-vec's\ninternal concern. SQL-side is the cleaner contract surface.\n\n## D6 — `vec_quantize_binary()` contract validation plan\n\nThe Pack 1 RED test is a round-trip:\n\n1. Build a known f32 vector `v` of length `<dim>` whose sign\n   pattern is hand-checkable.\n2. Insert via the writer path.\n3. Assert `vec_distance_hamming(embedding_bin, vec_quantize_binary(vec_f32(v))) = 0`.\n\nSpecified fixture (deterministic, no normalisation involved):\n\n```\ndim = 768.\nv[i] = +1.0 for i in 0..384, -1.0 for i in 384..768.\n```\n\nExpected `embedding_bin`: 384 set bits in the leading half, 384\nclear bits in the trailing half. Popcount = 384. The exact bit\nordering (LSB-first within each byte vs MSB-first) is an\nsqlite-vec internal contract; the round-trip via\n`vec_quantize_binary` guarantees both writer and reader see the\nsame packing, which is the only invariant the engine relies on.\n`vec_distance_hamming` against the same vector binarised the same\nway must be 0.\n\nOne fixture is sufficient. The previously-drafted secondary\n\"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed (its claim that\n`normalise([1,-1,1,-1,...])` and the half/half vector share\n\"identical sign patterns at every coordinate\" is wrong — one is\nhalf-positive/half-negative, the other alternates — see codex\nverdict finding 3). If P1-IMPL wants a second fixture for\ndefence-in-depth, the recommended shape is a vector that is +1\non every fourth coordinate and -1 elsewhere\n(`v3[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0` for dim=768): popcount\nof the quantization is exactly 192 set bits, trivially\nhand-checked, and clearly distinct from the half/half fixture's\npopcount of 384.\n\nValidation status: **empirical validation deferred to P1-IMPL's\nRED test.** A one-shot `sqlite3` confirmation against a temp DB\nwith `sqlite-vec` loaded was considered for this memo but\nrejected because (a) the Rust crate is the binding the writer\nactually uses and the sqlite3 CLI binding is a separate code\npath, (b) P1-IMPL's RED test exercises the engine writer\nend-to-end which is the only contract that matters, and (c) the\nbinary-quant guide\n(https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)\nalready documents the round-trip shape and `vec_distance_hamming`\nbehaviour. If the RED test surfaces a contract surprise (signed\nzero, NaN, byte-order), that is HITL escalation territory per\nthe ADR § 6 / \"vec_quantize_binary() input expectations\" — not\nsomething this design memo can resolve in advance.\n\nOpen-item linkage: the ADR § 6 third bullet calls out the\nfixture's \"atypically friendly\" sign-pattern concentration (mass\non 6 of 768 coordinates per `tests/perf_gates.rs:317`). That is a\nrecall-headroom concern for Pack 2, not a contract concern for\nPack 1. Pack 1's RED test is correctness, not recall.\n\n## D7 — Second writer site (test-only)\n\nConfirmed. The test-only helper at\n`Engine::write_vector_for_test` (`lib.rs:1806-1845`) is a second\ningest path that inserts into `vector_default` (line 1838). Pack 1\nmust update this site in lockstep with `commit_projection_outcomes`\nor it will violate the NOT NULL contract on `embedding_bin` /\n`source_type` / `kind` / `created_at` and break every test that\ngoes through `write_vector_for_test`.\n\nThe rewritten test helper insert is structurally identical to D5:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nPack 1 implementation MUST touch both:\n\n- `lib.rs:1832-1841` (test helper writer; the\n  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert at :1832-1836 also needs the\n  same `kind` value flow as `commit_projection_outcomes`).\n- `lib.rs:2845-2852` (production writer; D5 site).\n\nNo other writer site touches `vector_default`. The delete sites\n(`lib.rs:2177`, `:2265`) are unaffected — they target the row by\nrowid and the column changes are append-only at the schema level.\nThe writer-loop pins at `:2174`, `:2181`, `:2242` are not touched\n(they DELETE-by-rowid or operate on the shadow `_fathomdb_vector_rows`\ntable, not on the metadata columns being added).\n\n## D8 — Reader-path NO-OP guarantee\n\nThe Pack 2 reader rewrite is out of scope. The Pack 1 question is:\ndoes the **existing** reader at `read_search_in_tx`\n(`lib.rs:2317-2323`) keep working over the migrated schema?\n\nThe existing query is:\n\n```sql\nSELECT rowid FROM vector_default\nWHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1)\nORDER BY distance\nLIMIT 10\n```\n\n**Decision: confirmed no-op. The existing reader continues to\nreturn identical results post-migration.**\n\nReasoning:\n\n- The `embedding` column is **retained** (ADR § 2.1 \"the f32\n  `embedding` column is retained\"). Its declared type\n  `float[<dim>]` is unchanged.\n- vec0's MATCH semantics dispatch on the column referenced in the\n  predicate; adding sibling vector columns\n  (`embedding_bin bit[<dim>]`) and metadata columns\n  (`source_type`, `kind`, `created_at`) does not alter the\n  semantics of `embedding MATCH vec_f32(?)`.\n- The metadata + partition-key release blog\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html)\n  demonstrates a vec0 declaration with `partition key` + plain\n  metadata columns + the vector column, queried by the vector\n  predicate alone; the additional columns are filterable via\n  `WHERE` but do not become mandatory in the query shape.\n- The Pack 1 migration preserves the `rowid <-> write_cursor`\n  identity used throughout the writer loop (`lib.rs:2174-2175`\n  comment, `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`); the `INSERT INTO\n  vector_default_v2 ... SELECT v.rowid` clause is explicit\n  about it.\n\nAC-013 latency therefore stays at 2048 / 2327 ms post-Pack 1\n(matches the ADR § 4 / handoff § 1 stated contract). AC-019\nstays at its existing bound. AC-012 / AC-017 / AC-018 / AC-020\nare untouched because they do not query `vector_default`.\n\n## Open escalations\n\nNone. All eight decisions resolved against repo + cited external\ndocs. The pre-existing open items in the ADR § 6 (\"final numeric\nbudgets\", \"K-value selection\", \"fixture-friendliness for recall\")\nare Pack 2 concerns and are not affected by Pack 1.\n\n## Fix-1 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n\n- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n  list updated in D3.\n- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`), with repopulation through the existing\n  `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path\n  (`RebuildKind::Vec0`, `lib.rs:1947` and `lib.rs:2234-2289`).\n  The fabricated `operational_mutations` schema stamp is\n  removed. Cost baseline is the AC-013 562 s seed time\n  (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`),\n  with the rebuild expected materially under that since the\n  embedder does not re-run.\n- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":603,"oldLines":17,"newStart":603,"newLines":50,"lines":["   `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +","   `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7","   has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in","-  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`), with repopulation through the existing","-  `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `rebuild_shadow_state` path","-  (`RebuildKind::Vec0`, `lib.rs:1947` and `lib.rs:2234-2289`).","-  The fabricated `operational_mutations` schema stamp is","-  removed. Cost baseline is the AC-013 562 s seed time","-  (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`),","-  with the rebuild expected materially under that since the","-  embedder does not re-run.","+  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`). (Repopulation shape later replaced by","+  the fix-2 staged copy; see Fix-2 changelog below.)"," - **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary","   \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The","   half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test","   fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture","   (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is","   recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.","+","+## Fix-2 changelog","+","+Addresses codex BLOCK verdict at","+`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`","+(one new high finding on D4's repopulation semantics).","+","+- **Fix 2.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4 repopulation no","+  longer routes through `Engine::rebuild_vec0` /","+  `rebuild_shadow_state` (`RebuildKind::Vec0`). Verified against","+  the actual code: `run_projection_job` at","+  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2523-2557` calls","+  `embedder.embed(&job.body)` per row, and the rebuild test at","+  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`","+  locks in async drain semantics — both contradict the fix-1","+  claim that repopulation is synchronous and avoids the","+  embedder. D4 is replaced with a single SQL migration step","+  executed under `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`,","+  re-verified): (1) stage existing `vector_default` rows","+  JOIN-ed with `_fathomdb_vector_rows.kind` into a regular","+  staging table, (2) `DROP TABLE vector_default` + recreate","+  with the Pack 1 schema, (3) `INSERT ... SELECT` from staging","+  with `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side and a CASE expression","+  rendering the D3 `kind -> source_type` map, (4) drop the","+  staging table. Properties recorded explicitly: synchronous,","+  no embedder rerun, atomic under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`/`COMMIT`,","+  `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side once per row. Cost citation","+  updated: the AC-013 562 s seed figure is no longer cited as","+  a baseline because it includes embedder work this migration","+  avoids; budget remains the 60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate. A","+  \"Rejected alternative\" subsection added under D4 explaining","+  why `rebuild_vec0` is not used.","+- **Fix 2.2 (consequence).** D4 SQL-only migration shape is","+  justified against the actual `Migration { step_id: u32, sql:","+  &'static str }` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`","+  (re-verified) — pure SQL, no Rust callback extension point.","+  CASE WHEN is the migration-time mirror of the D3 helper","+  `resolve_source_type`; P1-IMPL is directed to add a","+  co-located drift-detection assertion."]}],"userModified":false,"replaceAll":false}}
